layers.nm: The Marangoni effect drives a continuous, chain-like flow that moves in a single direction.

s.t: The Marangoni effect drives a continuous, chain-like flow that moves in a single direction.

layers.nm: Inner molcules have no net force or pull.

s.t: Inner molcules have no net force or pull.

layers.nm: Surface molecules are pulled strongly inward.

layers.nm: Movement occurs from regions of low surface tension toward regions of high tension. The stronger pull at high tension areas generates a net directional flow, known as the Marangoni effect.

s.t: Movement occurs from regions of low surface tension toward regions of high tension. The stronger pull at high tension areas generates a net directional flow, known as the Marangoni effect.

layers.nm: Gene expression shapes E-cadherin levels across a gastruloid. Higher E-cadherin means stronger surface tension, creating differences that drive tissue flow toward high tension regions via the Marangoni effect.

s.t: Gene expression shapes E-cadherin levels across a gastruloid. Higher E-cadherin means stronger surface tension, creating differences that drive tissue flow toward high tension regions via the Marangoni effect.

layers.nm: During development, cells don’t just follow genetic instructions—they are also guided by physical forces and fluid dynamics that help establish an embryo’s structure.

s.t: During development, cells don’t just follow genetic instructions—they are also guided by physical forces and fluid dynamics that help establish an embryo’s structure.
